Classes, the unit of code.

In Java, almost everything lives inside a class. A class is a blueprint. It declares what data an object holds, which we call its fields, and what an object can do, which we call its methods. From that one blueprint you create objects, also called instances, using the keyword new. So one class describes the shape, and many instances all share that shape while each carries its own data.

Picture a Point class with two fields, x and y. It has a constructor that takes an x and a y and stores them, and a method that computes the distance from the origin. You make one point at three, four, and another at ten, zero, and each remembers its own coordinates. The first reports a distance of five, the second a distance of ten.

There are three shapes to register from that. First, fields are declared in the class body, outside any method, and each instance gets its own copy. Second, the constructor has the same name as the class and no return type, and it runs exactly once, when you create the object with new. And third, this is the implicit reference to the current instance; you reach for it when a parameter has the same name as a field, so that this dot x equals x means the field x of this instance takes the value of the parameter x.
